Welcome to Financial Economics

Valentinas Rudys

Fall 2025

Yes, we’ll cover saving, interest rates, investments, insurance, and even gambling—but we’ll do it through your lens. This course flips the traditional script: instead of starting with abstract models, we start with the real questions we all care about.

We’ll tackle things like:

  • How much should you borrow or save now—and a few years after graduation? Should you pay off your student loans early or invest instead? Do you need life insurance at 25?
  • How should your money be split between stocks, bonds, gold, and Bitcoin? Should your strategy change after a promotion—or a breakup?
  • Buy or lease a car? Sell it, trade it in, or rent it out on Turo? If you move, should you sell your house or rent it out? And how low must interest rates go before refinancing is worth it?
  • Is skipping health insurance ever smart? Should you insure your iPhone or your pet? And when—if ever—does buying a Powerball ticket make economic sense?

To answer these and many more real-world puzzles, you’ll build your own financial models from scratch, simulate decisions using Python or R, and compare your predictions to messy, real-world data. You won’t just learn the concepts—you’ll live them. You’ll develop intuition, ask sharper questions, and bridge the gap between elegant theory and everyday decisions. You will get opportunities to develop your interests into full-fledged research papers.

If you’re ready to face your future financial decisions with insight and confidence—this is the course for you.

The only prerequisite for the course is ECON 2010 or ECON 2020. If you are completing one of these prerequisite courses and want to concurrently enroll in this course, please reach out to me at valentinasrudys@weber.edu

For more information about this course, please visit https://valentinas500.github.io/finecon.html

Example Discussion 1: Consumption, Saving and Investing over the Lifecycle

Have you ever wondered how much you should be saving now—and how much you’ll be spending (or living off) later in life? The lifecycle hypothesis says that people generally save and invest when they’re younger and earning more, then spend those savings later when income drops—like in retirement. This pattern helps smooth out spending so life doesn’t feel like a rollercoaster of feast and famine.

In this course, you’ll build a simple model of saving behavior over your lifetime and test it against real-world data. But here’s the twist: the standard model often predicts too much spending in old age. Why? You’ll explore that question by improving the model, adding realistic features, and testing new ideas. Along the way, you’ll not only understand how financial behavior evolves over a lifetime—but also gain insight into your own financial future.

Example Discussion 2: Investing in Stocks over the Lifecycle

Ever wonder how much of your money should go into stocks versus safer options like bonds? We’ll build a model that predicts the “optimal” way to invest across your lifetime—and then compare it to what people actually do. Spoiler: the standard model says people should invest way more in stocks than they typically do.

In reality, fewer people own stocks at all, and even those who do often invest far less than the model suggests. Why the gap? You’ll dig into that question by tweaking the model and exploring what it leaves out—like how people really feel about risk, how income and age affect decisions, and how personal experiences shape behavior.

Then we’ll go beyond stocks and bonds to talk about gold, crypto, and other assets—so you can understand not just the theory, but how people actually invest, and how you might want to invest, too.

Example Discussion 3: Selling the House as an Option

Most of us do and will engage in decisions that can be regarded as options. Thus, after studying financial options, we will discuss real option contracts (right, but not the obligation, to make a business or personal decision in the future, where the value of that decision depends on how uncertain conditions unfold over time). Whether it’s your home, your job, or a wild bet on Elon, you’re constantly holding—and exercising—real-world options. The trick is learning when to hold, when to exercise, and when to cash out.
